Feedback from our fulfillment staff member "We're not activating transit requests....we're activating temp holds, patrons, etc...they just happen to involve items being put into transit.

   The activate feature is used to prioritize all types of requests i.e. move them to the top of the queue.  An item may have 2 requests that involve two different locations.   Only being able to use that feature once it arrives at a request location seems illogical. Nor does the online documentation state that is the case (but maybe they presume the requests involve the same location).  Additionally, if I wait until an item arrives at the hold location(1st request) and then try activating the 2nd request...it still puts the item back on the 'pick from shelf' step.
  So, the only time you can use 'Activate' is if the item has yet to be pulled.

I don't understand the usefulness or purpose. And the online documentation is sparse as well. "

This case was a mixed bag, and first off, I want to thank Jack Boettecher for getting to the bottom of our issue.  Essentially, there is a known issue with consortial collections, where the Ex Libris metadata librarians are not alerted to the presence of new content, when that content is uploaded by a consortia.  As a result, we have lost access to content for over a year in some instances because the files were not uploaded on Ex Libris' side.  This should be addressed by the vendor, not the customer, and as customers, we should not have to submit multiple error tickets to ensure that staff process these collections correctly.  In this particular case, I worked with Jack and the team at OhioLINK to update the consortial workflow, essentially asking their team to do double work and submit tickets that would explicitly alert the Ex Libris metadata team there was new content to upload.  While I appreciate Jack's troubleshooting immensely, this wasted both his time and mine -- the issue should have been addressed internally before it became such a widespread problem.

Except for the very short and direct answers I have received for the last couple of cases (things they could not be done because Alma cannot do them and it was suggested I submit the ideas to ELUNA/NERS)(change the font of the MDE to have a serif font and make the "local" bib 037 field searchable like the 035 (OCoLC), 945, 950 etc fields are)) I have not really been happy with Alma's support. 

The lost item case answers were confusing to me.  I asked what I thought was a very direct question and I received an over explanation that went the long way around reiterating what I asked. 

The case in question was: 

When does our Alma decide something is "lost?"  I had a case a while back where Alma was not charging the lost item replacement fee.  However, Alma sent a notification to a patron (barcode 2025001) that the four books he has checked out will be deemed lost if not returned soon.  The original due date on them is 29 April 2022.  

Alma should be set to send overdue notifications day due (or day after); 7 days alter; 14 days later; 21 days later; 30 days later; 45 days later, then at 60 days the item is considered "lost."  This did work for patron (barcode 2021003).  Alma has not assessed fines to patron barcode 2025001 though.  It does seem that the wording has been altered/changed in the emails since the case I opened about it not assessing the lost item replacement fee from the item record.  It does look like some of the overdue notification have included the lost item processing fee in the past.  Maybe I am reading it incorrectly.  

Is there a way to prevent the lost item processing and lost item replacement fees from showing up on the overdue emails until the item is actually due or is this Alma's gentle way of telling patrons how much the fines could cost if the item is determined to be lost as opposed to just having an overdue fine?

The gist of the case was: 

When does our Alma decide something is "lost?"  I had a case a while back where Alma was not charging the lost item replacement fee.  However, Alma sent a notification to a patron (barcode 2025001) that the four books he has checked out will be deemed lost if not returned soon...
Is there a way to prevent the lost item processing and lost item replacement fees from showing up on the overdue emails until the item is actually due or is this Alma's gentle way of telling patrons how much the fines could cost if the item is determined to be lost as opposed to just having an overdue fine? 

The answer was long. 

I did not need another explanation of the overdue lost/loan profile because there is a previous case in my history where an overdue lost/loan issue was fixed. 

In the middle of the answer was what I needed to know: 

...the fines we can see in that letter were not actually assessed since those items were not declared lost...

So yes, then the letter is showing the potential total fines/fees if the patron fails to return the items.  It IS Alma's way of gently nudging the patron to return the books. 

Overall, I am very dissatisfied with Alma's support team (except for the couple of times I called an Yaala (sp?) answered the phone and helped/directed me to help because she is very friendly (she had directed me to help before when we had Voyager) I really like Alma much more than Voyager and I am dissatisfied with this new support/ticket system it is bulky and confusing (but if we still had Voyager I would have to use it so I am stuck with it), but I am very satisfied with Alma.  

In the meantime I think I will resort to the Alma listserv and start opening tickets as a very last resort.  I wish your team was as good a Voyagers support.
